The government wants to stop the torture of "witches" and has issued a brochure
Women who are branded witches in Burkina Faso usually share some common social characteristics.
They are more likely to be older, they cannot find work - for example, for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
If one of these women "becomes" a witch, she is strictly isolated so that she cannot become a danger to the rest of the village.
"Men are rarely affected by this fate".
"Even young and healthy women are spared this, as they help with work and give birth", describes one religious sister, who cares for more than a hundred women who have been expelled from their communities in a special home in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso.
The local government decided to take action against this abnormal "social action".
And for that reason, he issued a brochure to stop the "witch hunt".
But there's a catch.
"More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read", the newspaper der Standard pointed to the dilemma of written enlightenment.
But witchcraft is common in other African countries.
In Ghana, the neighboring country of Burkina Faso, 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahová was tortured to death by three women and two men - they poured oil on her and simply lit her up.
The BBC server also reported on the incident.
However, the perpetrators claimed that the matter was merely a coincidence of unfortunate circumstances.
According to her version, the oil is ignited, used for ritual anointing.
After the group tried to "eject an evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" supports the people here regardless of their education.
The Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: "Women who break human souls were a danger in the past as they are today".
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to de-escalate the witch hunt, the Gambian president himself has been involved in the process last year.
"President Yahya Jammeh started a monstrous witch hunt after his aunt's death, as they allegedly had a hand in their deaths and were now trying to kill the president himself through black magic".
"He called for help from shamans from nearby Guinea who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president's bodyguards, forcibly abducted women and men from Gambian villages and brought them to the president's farm in Kanilai", Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the imprisoned were forced to drink a waste of plants that had hallucinogenic effects, but which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the people arrested did not survive the stay on the farm.
Only because of international pressure were the nearly a thousand prisoners released.
A tenant of Bakala: He heats in the oven, yet pays higher rent
An elderly man is leaving the RPG Byty customer centre of the "coal baron" Zdeněk Bakala, the largest private owner of rented apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm was a briefcase with three new leases for three apartments: for his own and the apartments of his daughters and his son, who is serving a prison sentence.
All three were just raised in rent under the so-called "de-regulation".
Instead of 3,500 crowns a month, the son is to spend 4,100 crowns next year on a two-room apartment with a second-class kitchen.
"And there is not even running hot water in the apartment and you have to heat it in a simple coal oven", he angrily ticks his finger on his son's new lease, for which he has a power of attorney.
"But what - I signed", he explains half displeased and half resigned.
The citizens' association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new lease terms as 'incorrect and immoral', advises tenants not to sign the new contracts and to wait until 7 December to publish a guide on how to proceed against such contracts.
But the man just waves.
"One says this, the other says that", he makes a dark face.
The region of Ostrava is thus becoming a major 'de-regulation laboratory'.
After the new year, this deregulation is expected to affect most rental properties in the Czech Republic, whose tenants have not yet paid market-based rent.
Aktuálně.cz therefore decided to visit this "lab" personally.
The waiting room in Havířov is one of four in the Ostrava region and already at nine o'clock this Tuesday morning is breaking full.
Right next to the door, there's a security guard with a call machine.
"Rent 2011", that's how a special keypad on the touchscreen lights up.
You type in a short time, the device will spit out a number plate.
We've barely decoded the number "157" and it's already beeping on the big screen on the ceiling of the waiting room.
Half a second later, it's your turn.
A little later, an older couple enters the waiting room to ask about the rent, but the rush in the waiting room does not seem to apply to the new rent.
Most people are here to solve the usual problems - repair requests, insurance issues and the like.
From mid-November, the new lease agreements in the Ostrava region will flatten the mailboxes of most tenants of the RPG portfolio's 44,000 apartments.
RPG Byty has written to them proposing a rental increase of about 15 to 38 percent.
The special switch for new rents in the customer centre has been open since 18 November.
"The campaign is going on for a week, so this is just the beginning", the ladies behind the counter reply after a moment's hesitation, as the "client" reveals himself as a journalist.
Deregulation and Bakala's former mining habitations are a hot topic.
Before the elections, the deputy parliamentary president from Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek, from the ČSSD, had raised the issue quite loudly, no wonder the newspapers are full of it today.
"Twenty years I want them to have a new floor".
"Never in my life have I been able to replace them with toilet glasses", says the man mentioned earlier.
The staff say that the main task now is for pensioners to check whether they will actually receive the promised RPG rental reduction if they sign the special offer in time.
The other tenants who sign the new lease before 15 December will also be able to take advantage of a half-reduced February rent.
But until now, the "de-regulation switch" in Havířov is anything but overwhelmed with demand.
"Of the 360 customers we had yesterday, only about 40 to 50 were renting here in 2011", the switchbeds estimate.
RPG offers individual rental agreements on its websites and wallpapers wherever necessary.
However, if the parties do not agree on the new lease, it shall be determined by an independent court.
"This is not meant to be a threat, but is meant to be information about the only possible and fully legitimate legal process", RPG explains on its websites.
"No one is going to court here", says one of the employees of RPG Byty, and a man on the street outside the customer centre is at least partially right.
"I have 13,000 (KR) pensions, of which I have 5,000 left over for food, where should I get the money for a court case", he says.
Then the employee will be insecure.
"I'll see you around".
"Mr. Zaorálek tells them through the media not to sign and so people wait", she reflects.
The regulated lease ends in most of the Czech Republic on New Year's Day 2011 and according to RPG Byty, the increase in rent is an economic necessity.
'The existing rent level is not even sufficient to maintain the housing fund,' argues Pavel Klimeš, director of the housing portfolio of RPG Byty, and - in the opinion of the homeowners, the main reason for the increase is the neglect of the housing fund, which has been criticized by the tenants who have paid off.
While RPG was able to invest 4 billion in the apartments from rented rentals between 2005 and 2010, it is expected to invest 5,2 billion in the four years from 2011 to 2014.
On the large LCD display on the ceiling opposite the upholstery seats in Havířov's waiting room, some red-lighting information is constantly showing up.
'The 2011 rental increases of 15% and less concern 31 200 dwellings, or more than 90% of RPG dwellings.'
"This always means a maximum of CZK 7.50 per square metre per month", is read on the LCD monitor.
Just 400 apartments from the RPG portfolio will increase rent by 38 percent.
'In these cases, it is an increase in extremely low rental prices of CZK 19.66 per square metre,' RPG argues.
For 2,600 apartments, the rent will remain the same next year.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not boost rents in a leap, but will be done gradually within four to eight years.
Moreover, the company imposes a further obligation: all the income from the increase in rent (see chart) is to be returned to the dwellings, especially in terms of heat savings - in new windows and in thermal insulation.
- the first is to benefit those who sign the agreements on the increase in rent.
The architects looked in - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten here, with everything that goes with it: colorful walls, creative furniture, lots of toys, and even a mini-gaming area on the outdoor terrace.
This preschool has been available to the staff of Arch.Design since last year.
The architectural and design office Arch.Design, which has a number of well-known Brünner buildings, has been working on the premises for its mini-children's garden since the first designs for the new building.
It is a good idea, because most of its 90 employees are in the baby boom era and the company is committed to getting the designers back to work as soon as possible.
Along with the possibility of working for a shorter period, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the context of its social programme.
It is easier for civil engineers and architects to put their demanding profession and childcare under one roof.
The mini-kindergarten is an original idea of the staff at Arch.Design and with the support of the management they have been able to win grants from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The mini-kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operational Programme from the European Social Fund and the Czech Republic's State budget.
This financing (grants of CZK 2.8 million) enabled the necessary facilities and equipment to be provided and qualified staff and operations were provided for a period of two years.
After the funding has been exhausted (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the miniature nursery for another 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the firm Economy Rating providing active assistance in the application process.
The children are cared for by a qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher - who can visit the kindergarten without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini-kindergarten, only five children are allowed to attend at the same time, but the day changes over several children.
The nursery is flexible to meet the needs of parents, whose children have the same rights as all employees in the use of the nursery - regardless of the hierarchy of companies and their respective positions.
Although individual education and care is involved, the content of the mini-kindergarten programme is nevertheless comparable to the pre-school framework programme.
The children not only play here, but above all they are taught excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to preschool, they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to the children.
What is more, the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can look at the children at any time and thus relieve the stress of having children pick up late from a distant kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
No wonder natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also emerging.
Arch.Design was one of the Czech companies that offered significant benefits in recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personnel marketing through such programmes.
A bone house is still fascinating after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are ripped fishmills.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
The local people gave the house the nickname "Bonehouse" because of its organic forms.
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile scraps and mosaics, the shell-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines are all characteristics of Antonio Gaudi's youthful style.
The façade of the house is a play with beautiful lines, delicate colors and textures that remind nature and living creatures.
Only when you look closely do you notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the entire façade is more plastic, dramatic, and the special lighting enhances the brightness of the colors.
The same fluid lines and curved shapes dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even viewing holes and decks.
The Batlló House in the Eixample district on Passeig de Grácia shopping street No. 43 was built by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese in 1877.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but eventually he agreed with Gaudí's idea of an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
But Antoni Gaudí did not design the Casa Batlló alone.
He worked with architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his dashboard that the decorations for the real estate owner's representative apartment were created and the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other painters and artists also worked on the facade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá in Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given its organic shape by the local inhabitants because of the nickname "Bonehouse".
Others called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "going house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a central heating system for the house, unique to the time, with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces.
Something bizarre is suggesting her 45-degree inclination.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations of the time and did not let himself be misled by them.
Although he obtained the city's approval before construction began, his information on the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, when the city fathers finished it, they were so horrified by the result that they demanded a remedy.
The Council members also found that the building with its pillars even entered the public sidewalk.
However, no further changes were made, quite the contrary - only 15 days after the request of the district Josep Batlló submitted an application for the lease of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
The second floor gallery had a social room, and the third floor had the bedroom and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewellery store.
The entire six-story building runs through a staircase to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the conversion eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of interconnecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the living room doors, so that a larger society can talk comfortably without having to forgo some intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house was renovated by Gaudí and, in addition to a new facade, it was given a rather unusual roof and two more floors.
Gaudí's play with light, as well as the blue and white glazed tiles that cover the courtyard and the lighthouses, are also impressive.
The play of these two colors gives the highest degree of light to all floors of the house.
He simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors, which absorb sunlight on the contrary.
The Casa Batlló, which was inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, is now open to all.
The first floor is the most spacious and elegant apartment open to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only in the year, on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When they found that this was a fairly lucrative business, they kept the visits, and they extended them to other common and rooftop rooms, including the roof terrace.
The price for visiting the monument is not a pencil, however, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and tourist pass holders get a 20 percent discount.
This is more than the entrance fees for other Gaudi buildings in the city.
If you want to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the occupants and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bedrest?
Not the best bed frame, but the quality of the surface - so mattresses and rust make the good bed.
However, these must be complemented in a harmonious way to meet the specific needs of the user.
Many factors play a role in the selection process - weight, size, health status and, last but not least, the sex of the sleeper.
The interior of the mattress and the roast must be equally important.
Typical example?
In a home that does not receive regular heating over the weekend, latex mattresses are not well suited because they take much longer to "warm up".
In addition, they are significantly heavier than regular polyurethane mattresses.
And they should be turned around regularly.
If they do not have enough vent in the core and are still on a solid plate, moisture builds up, so it is not excluded that they form under the mold.
Of course, what you're used to is also a factor in choosing.
Those who have been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with a soft layer are common, will find it difficult to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
"All the ice hockey players who came back from the NHL complained to me that they can't sleep properly here anymore".
"For their slender shoulders, buttocks, and hips, they simply need a soft layer of visco foam".
"I recommend this, among other things, for people with diabetes who suffer from a nervous system disorder that makes them unable to receive the 'information' from the joints and skin", explains Sylva Hadamcziková, a specialist in upholstery furniture.
So many years ago, I got many ice hockey players and other customers these memory foam mattresses.
'Today this is no longer a problem, as such mattresses are offered by Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex and the Czech manufacturer Tropico, among others.'
And you don't have to be a famous ice hockey player to appreciate the benefits of visco foam.
This "miracle" actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the heat absorbed, or in other words, it is directly attached to the warm body.
Nowhere is it pushing, you don't roll around at night like after a hard fight.
You just sleep a lot better.
The viscoelastic foam also provides protection against decubitus (burn).
When choosing the size of the mattress, the length of the soles of the feet should still be taken into account for the size of the body, which is about 21 to 34 cm.
Men and women who are at least 180 cm tall need a bed that is 210 to 220 cm long.
Each sleeper should have at least 90 cm of bed width, or 180 cm.
In single beds, for example in single beds, 120 to 140 cm are appropriate.
For the convenience of visitors.
