More and more parents want human-monitoring devices to keep their kids in check.
The fear of their own children is growing, and more and more parents are considering monitoring them using GPS.
The system, which was originally invented to track down cars, can locate people just as well, which would be helpful in cases like the recent untraced disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette case, but soon it is not likely to be larger than a wristwatch.
Many people are terrified of the missing Anička and are looking for ways to better protect their children.
And for the price of compromising their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not a case of espionage, but an effective way of reducing the likelihood of tragedy", says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting them in someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have never had such cases before".
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons", adds Pilin.
But he feels that the child should always know what the box is for and how to use it in an emergency.
However, child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not like to wear such a thing, it simply gets rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity when it comes to deliberately losing things when they don't want to be controlled".
"At first, parents were very much expecting mobile phones, but they can be switched off just as easily as these new surveillance devices", says Mrs Bočková.
In your opinion, it is also controversial whether such a facility actually helps in the event of an attack.
"In planned abductions, the kidnapper will almost always check whether the child has any electronic equipment to locate him".
"It's the phone today".
"If such surveillance devices were to be used more widely, they would also look for them, as their sale would certainly be accompanied by mass advertising".
"In these cases, the criminals are always one step ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
However, it admits that similar devices can be helpful in the event of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
According to Roberta Čech of RC Monitoring, which provides tracking services for both automobiles and people, the existence of such a device can help even if it is destroyed immediately after the attack.
"The device can be set to report the position at certain intervals".
"Even if it were destroyed immediately, at least the last position of the person concerned is available".
"More expensive devices even have a tilt gauge built in, meaning that if you fall and remain motionless, the device immediately sends a warning indicating the position", says Mr Čech.
He believes that similar services could also be used by smart phones with navigation, but only to play a specific software.
