A longer index finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of cancer
Men with a thumb longer than a ring finger are obviously at lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
It's supposed to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially in men up to 60", said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the University of Warwick's Cancer Research Institute.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health issues, Ms Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in the UK followed more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients, but also 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had a shorter index finger on their right hand than their ring finger.
These men had the same likelihood of prostate cancer as 19 percent of men with ring and index fingers.
However, for men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, the risk dropped by 33 percent, and for men up to sixty, by 87 percent.
The ratio of the lengths of the two fingers mentioned, which are already formed at prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones that the child was exposed to in the womb.
Less testosterone is the same as a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that speeds up the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told ČTK that he was only briefly aware of this study, but he still did not believe the relationship between finger length and cancer risk had been "fully proven".
