Arsenic-resistant microbes could create new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a foreign bacterial species that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists have discovered this unusual bacterium here on earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered vital.
"This organism has two possibilities".
"It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow".
"That makes it very special, even though it's almost a kind of 'foreign' life form", explained Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
So far, six main elements have been considered essential for life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But as scientists have found, the bacteria in Mono Lake, California, grow even more when they replace phosphorus with arsenic.
"You wonder what else is possible", said co-author Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, Anbar says.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details of the discovery were made has given rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report may be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that organisms can start biochemical processes in other planetary systems with the help of other elements and that the 'standard elements' that we believe are absolutely necessary for life are not necessarily fixed", explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at Milton Keynes Open University in the United Kingdom.
Cockel wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another", Cockell added.
This discovery was not a coincidence.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high content of arsenic.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she assumed that microbes exposed to both could possibly replace one element with another.
"Arsenic's toxicity is primarily due to its chemical behavior similar to that of phosphorus".
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another".
"But the difference is so great that arsenic works differently than phosphorus, entering our biochemical system, where it lubricates virtually everything", Anbar explains.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing concentration of arsenic, which adapted and grew.
While the microbes grow better in phosphorus, their ability to survive in arsenic also shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a lecturer in microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, which is why science has assumed that early life forms used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than in the early Earth age", said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
