Can politeness bind the breakup?
After a campaign of slander and negativity, little politeness has broken out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of a real bipartisan cooperation or a moment of illusion before you quickly return to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting between President Obama and top congressmen on Tuesday did not bring about a breakthrough in the big issues to be addressed during the so-called "lame duck session", the meeting at the end of a government period in which no decisions are made.
From what we hear, it was neither a polite discussion between two different parties nor a respect for their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of a party-listed score.
The President's public meeting of the Committee on the Deficit on Wednesday was similarly civilized, despite the political differences that continue to exist between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates mutual respect that masks the ideological divide that continues to separate members.
That's hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - one demanding the other's sign of cooperation and compromise, while trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after a new party war.
The meeting itself on Tuesday and its assessment by the participants were therefore limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, donations, health care or the arts, the two sides are miles apart.
Finally, the November elections have been a mild vote for Washington for a short time.
"No question, the tone has changed", said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"This is inevitable after the election.
Elections are a party passion that dies out again.
And that's good".
In some questions, especially those on the agenda of the lame duck session, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution.'
Bush's tax cuts are coming to an end this year, and no one's supporting it.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or all of them, whether temporary or permanent.
Similarly, a compromise on the increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because Republicans cannot afford to believe that the preferred tax cuts for the rich are being made while they deny support to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting in the White House, there has been increased optimism that these issues can be agreed during the lame duck session and ratified at the same time as the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on urgent issues of the lame duck session "does not necessarily lead to lasting cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of inconsistency is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
"After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will be turned into confrontation", he said.
Wehner is also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - that courtesy leads to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what's happening from now until 2012 as a pre-struggle, or shadow box, for the main event of 2012", he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the rise of the new Republican majority in the White House and the tea party voters who served their formation.
As worried as Republican leaders may be about playing too much poker, they know they need to try to keep their promises to cut government spending and roll back health care reform.
These lines are already evident in the first reactions to the Commission's recommendations on deficits, which include tax reform and the raising of certain taxes, the raising of the retirement age and the reduction of public expenditure.
Vice-Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have pressed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes in the Commission to make their plan an official recommendation and they are struggling hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the Committee, since in financial matters, at least today, there is little room for compromise or sympathy.
Galston predicts two phases in the battle between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take place next year in the form of party collisions, when Republicans challenge Obama on the state budget, taxes and health care system, followed later by a larger phase of bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It is proven that despite the biases of the current election, the majority of Americans still wish the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, both sides must be careful about public reaction.
Whoever's condemned to lose will have to change course and find a compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Party and polarization are bigger today than they were in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a bigger ideological divide between Obama and the congressional Republicans than it was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans back then.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a pure prelude to a much wider election of 2012 in terms of consequences.
The courtesy shown this week is welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find common ground in the issues that still separate the two.
