Sports and leisure
Tricks like Alonso and Ramos's in the Ajax game show inventiveness, but not the will to evade a penalty.
The allegedly exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 game against Ajax in the Champions League led to much speculation as to whether or not it was an unsportsmanlike act and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is common knowledge, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee would show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead their group, the two players will meet the sanction imposed on them in the next league match against Auxerre and thus enter the next stage without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under these or similar circumstances is not a new practice; it is more common in the world of football.
It's so widespread that it's part of the ethos -- the unwritten rules that are followed in this sport.
Part of the debate surrounding the case is that a team from Real Madrid (who in their anthem praises virtue and honor and on other occasions punished their players for similar incidents) played the lead role, and that Mourinho dramatized the story by adding an episode to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is whether this behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions are an infraction of the rules.
In this respect, the damage to the spirit of sport should be investigated.
The spirit of sports is defending the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not compromised by these actions because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the opposing players taking unjustified advantage of the opposing team.
The paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not correspond to what we normally mean by a foul game or circumvention of the rules, because circumvention of the rule was usually not done in secret to avoid a penalty, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and happily accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders derived from the deliberate fouls.
It should be emphasised here that the rival was neither put at a disadvantage nor benefited from the game played, as the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It's also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club doesn't have those players.
The advantage is obviously that players can start the next Champions League game phase without playing cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term advantage, to some extent uncertain, because the team could eventually withdraw, and the players with this procedure also receive a penalty and move on to the second card cycle, where they withdraw less than in the first cycle because of card accumulation.
It is not clear whether this is really an advantage.
In the end, such practices are not contrary to the spirit of sport, which includes strategic decisions to make the most of the rules.
