Luisa Valenzuela read a text dedicated to Gonzalo Celorio, and Shultz described it as a great story afterwards. Luisa tells in the first person and is the protagonist who is looking to learn what a "wound" is, and goes from doctor to doctor, from whom she does not get an answer, but clues to the guide to her story.
She leaves the infectious disease specialist convinced, "Patience is not my strength, maybe it is my wound".
Finally, after a frustrating approach to the trauma specialist who took her breath away in the middle of the walk, but who explained to her that wound is not a scientific term, the psychoanalyst reveals the secret: "The wound is the real open, the symbolic is the scar".
The main character of the story sighs, relieved, and concludes that she "only learned from the wound that it was really open and did not exist".
Valenzuela, the writer, played with them.
The Nicaraguan Sergio Ramírez also presented a delightful account, which he called the "Lob of the Invention", in which the finger in the wound is not mentioned but is discovered.
With allusions to magical realism, he tells of a famous witch who touched the clouds, brought back men who had travelled far, or restored the virtue lost by a girl. The tale made a turn and told of America, the great novel that was not lacking from the beginning in its own chronicles, and he quoted Bernal Díaz del Castillo, who criticized the abundance of stories told by the conquerors.
"Cervantes, who invited us all (the writers), mocked the false witnesses who appeared in the stories portrayed as true, but otherwise the history of America would never have been told - with an imagination that even the sense of shame was lost".
However, he emphasizes that "the crazy and the liar are the ones who imagine things best", and that is where reality and lies come closer together, where you no longer know which side the story belongs to, where fictional literature reaches its peak.
He actually calls it the "Cervantes tradition".
"We inherited from him the story of being told".
When Mayra Montero was in her turn, the author commented and praised the variety of interpretations that the invitation of the FIL to the round table of 'The Finger in the Wound' had contributed to.
The Cuban and Puerto Rican woman dedicated her contribution to the great wound of social violence that is affecting her country - as well as all of Latin America - as a result of the drug trafficking struggles.
"I believe that good literature, good poetry, good songs contain a silent, unplanned commitment", she explained, after stressing that literature is communication and a bond that builds between the author and the readers as if it were a "chemical reaction".
The evening was decided by the Spanish poet Luis García Montero, whose contribution also raised "this finger of the committed writer in the wound of the writer".
He noted that in a fast-paced world, intellectual habits and control of consciousness also lead to dogmatism, forgetting "that behind every affirmation there is a little no and behind every denial a little yes".
"To possess our thoughts and reality, we must nuance: and nuance often means putting our finger in the wound and harassing those who feel much more comfortable thinking in the form of caricatures, in black and white, in prefabricated ideas without nuances, and harassing the powerful who prefer to divide the world into black and white", he noted, inviting them to rediscover the meaning of writing.
