The United States is changing the rules for obtaining a visa
The persons must present themselves to the visa application service before their interview at the consulate, thus reducing the costs of waiting times.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa at the United States Embassy and Consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants must introduce themselves to the visa application service (ASC) before they are interviewed at the consulate.
The ASC staff shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be verified by the consulate before the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be reduced as the deadline, processing of the visa application and the transport service that hands out the document will no longer be required to be paid separately.
The applicant shall only make a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa with application (including temporary visa for employees) and $390 for handlers and investors.
Those who wish to renew their visas do not have to have a conversation at the consulate, they only have to present themselves at the nearest ASC, where they will submit their documents and be fingerprinted.
As biometric data are collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment to the consulate will stay there less than before.
Those applying for visas at the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the $26 service fee.
Further information on the new visa application procedure can be found at http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
