Avenging Hackers and Scamers
The WikiLeaks affair has a double meaning.
On the one hand, it has emerged as an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sinister hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at international level and gives a taste of a future dominated by regression.
But let's take it one by one.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that every file created by an intelligence agency (an x-favorite nation) is made up entirely of newspaper clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits are nothing more than what you've been reading for months in every X-popular journal (except those owned by Berlusconi), and the terrifyingly caricatured profile of Gaddafi has long been a source of substance for cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files should only be made up of already known news is essential for the dynamics of intelligence, and not only in this century.
If you go to a library devoted to esoteric publications, you will find that every work (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosary Cruisers) repeats exactly what was already written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (or because he did not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who practice the occult believe only in what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also Dan Brown's success mechanism.
So is the secret.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited in mind) is also the head of the intelligence service (otherwise he could be anything, for example, editor at Libération), who only considers true what he acknowledges.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as the one that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why was such a crackdown on the disclosures of these files?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person knows, that the embassies - at least since the end of World War II and since then, when heads of government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and have become spy centres, except for some small representative functions.
Any spectator of investigative films knows this very well, and it's not hypocritical to ignore it.
Nevertheless, the fact that it is repeated publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and serves to cast American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that an X-Rated hacker can tap into the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a major blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Moreover, the scandal is less a victim-driven affair than a "slaying of the slain".
But let's focus on the profound nature of what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell's time, you could unite all power like a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy could have been perfectly correct since then, where you could control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel you visited, the highway you chose, and so on; the citizen would become a total victim of the eye of the power.
But if you think about what's happening today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control process stops being one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen as the citizen's avenger - can uncover the secrets of power.
But how can a power hold on when it can no longer keep its own secrets?
It's true, Georg Simmel has already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it's also true that any knowledge of Berlusconis or Merkels' character is basically a secret free of secrets, as it reveals the public sphere; but to reveal in the style of WikiLeaks that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets is to deprive them of any power.
WikiLeaks did not wrong Sarkozy or Merkel, but Clinton and Obama did.
What will be the consequences of this abuse inflicted on such a mighty power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer post any reserved information online - which would be like a street corner hanging.
But it's also obvious that with the latest technology, it's futile to hope to keep confidential phone records secret.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state has been on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How could private relationships, which are for certain ears only, be maintained in the future?
I know very well that my prediction at the moment sounds like science fiction and romantic, but I feel compelled to imagine the government agents secretly moving on uncontrollable routes, carrying their messages with them nowhere but in mere memory, and beyond that, hiding the few written information they've got in the shoebox.
The information would be stored in a single copy in closed drawers: basically, Watergate's espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is advancing like cancer these days, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet is reconstructing a telegraph with (telephone) wire.
The (analog) videotapes had enabled film researchers to explore a film tape by tape by coiling it backwards and forward and uncovering all the secrets of assembly, while the (numerical) CDs nowadays only allow them to jump from chapter to chapter, in macro proportions.
High-speed trains take three hours from Rome to Milan, while flying takes three and a half hours, including the transition.
It is therefore not uncommon for politics and communication technology to come back to cars and horses.
One last observation.
In earlier times, the press tried to understand what kind of secrets were being forged between the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that demand confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France is making good on its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine the compliance of the rapidly resolved financing pledges (also called 'fast start' or early financing) implemented by developing countries.
And the French cosmetics are already exposed.
The Copenhagen Treaty pledged developing countries to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has pledged EUR 7.2 billion over three years, France EUR 1.26 billion (i.e. 420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU pulled all the registers to convince its partners of its commitment to fast-start financing: detailed progress report from its Member States, press conference, major side events, brochure distribution.
The operation is remarkable and appreciated for its true value: developing countries and civil society are happy to see all developed countries doing the same thing at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if you look at the details, things are a little more complicated.
This money should be 'new and additional' under the Copenhagen Treaty to ensure that additional expenditure is made without prejudice to public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the benchmark they consider best.
The EU Commission has chosen, for example, the target for 2009: international funding will be maintained and 150 million will be added over three years under the 'fast start' financing.
Other countries have chosen similar guidelines, either in terms of year or terms at the level of public development aid.
In contrast, France considered that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 was 'new and additional'.
In other words, there are no guidelines for the previous year's expenditure or for public development aid at global level.
In particular, the total French support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) - France claims to comply with its commitment to 'new and additional' financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There's no rule yet, and everyone chooses their own computing mode.
Some, such as France, find 1 € borrowed as equivalent to 1 € donated.
The Commission has already decided to take a decision on the proposal.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often projects linked to emission controls based on the most efficient technology) can be justified, it is misleading to present the euro as the equivalent of a donated euro... Moreover, only the cost of the loan to the donor country should be counted as the commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing else in mind than the following view: it 'respects' its €420 million commitment by taking in 91.5% of loans (€389.8 million) and donating 8.5% of €36.1 million) - see also the EU document to convince yourself of this.
France is the only EU country that uses loans in large part.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are 100% committed to donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to meet its commitments, France pays just 10 cents and understands a comparable commitment.
That's a good hockey shot.
In general, France operates with a double-edged approach to its fast-start financing: partly with the development of action over time and partly with the reality of financial use.
France manages to make it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Treasury Department (as it seems that Bercy was the one who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative effect: once within the EU (why do the other Member States continue to donate if they can borrow enough?) and then in the negotiations, since developing countries cannot be completely deceived...
The chapter on early financing is only a small question for a relatively short time compared to the whole of climate discussions.
But it could be too much of a drop in the huge machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
However, it is essential to learn his lesson from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its accounting for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and of balanced equity with the other countries of the European Union.
France could, however, advance the debate on the issue of longterm financing (another crucial and currently debated issue): the question of the 'accountability' or the accounting of its loans is not avoided.
France could change its position to be as progressive on the issues of dispute as it is on other matters.
The hope is therefore based on the new environment minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement of France's fast start and its vision of 'accountability' and the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
Alarm - Pesticides taken by children
A 10-year-old child consumes 81 different chemicals per day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Association Générations Futures (formerly the rights and respect movement for future generations).
The association, which states that its results "do not reflect a statistically significant value given the small number of samples analysed but are illustrative of the problematic nature of the problem", had purchased the food normally consumed by a four-year-old child at meals and an intermediate meal at supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September.
These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - were studied, as were snacks from laboratories looking for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance sheet is shattering: 81 chemicals, including 42 classified as potentially or likely carcinogenic and five classified as safe carcinogenic, as well as 37 substances with endocrine disrupting factor, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
'Even if the legal limits for each individual chemical taken are not exceeded in the approximate total of cases, the fact that the consumer is potentially exposed to carcinogens or endocrine disrupting substances is a matter of concern is well understood from this survey,' the association notes.
Already at breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than 10 of the residues that may cause cancer and three have been shown to be safe as carcinogens, as well as more than 20 residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, which was meant as a snack for the study, has traces of six chemicals, including a banned fungicide in France.
The same is true for the green beans from Kenya, including lunch, where the study found traces of a strictly prohibited insecticide in the EU.
In addition, the hawksteak, tuna from the box, even the baguette and chewing gum were spiked with pesticides and other chemicals.
The analysis of the tap water revealed the presence of nitrates and chlorophyll.
At dinner, the salmon steak was the "richest" with 34 detected chemical residues, and even the plastic kettle used to heat the meal in the microwave was not untouched.
The ultimate risk of this "pollutant cocktail" to consumers "is likely to be underestimated", the study says.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV) has proposed, in view of the urgency of the situation, a moratorium on the use of pesticides to halt the 'increase in diseases of civilization'.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
